      • binarySearchArray

        public <T> Notes.Node binarySearchArray(T[] arr,
                                        T value)
        A NOTE ON QUICKSORT AND MERGE SORT: Interesting note on quickSort and mergeSort with regards to stability: - http://cafe.elharo.com/programming/java-programming/why-java-util-arrays-uses-two-sorting-algorithms/ Basically, stability doesn't matter for primitive data types because you're not dealing with pointers, a 6 is the same as a 6 if they're both ints, whereas "6" and "6" may have different pointers depending on variable name. That's why Arrays.sort uses quickSort for primitives but mergeSort for objects. Apparently quickSort is faster.
